    <text>
    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>Sept 22<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 1880</date>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Ch. Darwin regrets much that it is impossible for him to have the honour &amp; pleasure of accepting Sir J. Mason’s invitation to Luncheon on October 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>. or for him to attend Prof. Huxleys opening Address.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">For CD’s invitation to the opening of Mason Science College, Birmingham, on 1 October 1880, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12721F.xml">letter from Josiah Mason, [before 22 September 1880]</ref>. The opening was marked by an address by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2486.xml">Thomas Henry Huxley</ref> titled ‘Science and culture’, and printed in <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 7 October 1880, pp. 545–8.</note>
        </div>
    
